Name: Deneb. Type: double star, pulsating variable star. Constellation: Cyg. Azimuth Angle: 315.4657797133095 degrees. Altitude Angle: 28.63345586345168 degrees. Description: Deneb () is a blue supergiant star in the constellation of Cygnus. It is the brightest star in the constellation and the 19th brightest in the night sky, with an apparent magnitude slightly varying between +1.21 and +1.29. Deneb is one of the vertices of the asterism known as the Summer Triangle and the "head" of the Northern Cross. Its Bayer designation is α Cygni, which is Latinised to Alpha Cygni, abbreviated to Alpha Cyg or α Cyg.